<font color="#FF0000">GREAT STATE OF TENNESSEE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Oct  7 17:45:56 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
Come on over to Tennessee any time you like and I will show you true hospitality and friendship. I will even take you to the Appalachian Trail which is a few miles from here. It runs along the North Carolina - Tennessee State Line. We can carry day packs and canteens, and I know a beautiful long forgotten old trail that is no longer blazed. I don't know if you are up to it - old and cranky as you are.<br><br>
Guaranteed to be a tough hump - just as pretty countryside as the 'Nam and we don't have to worry about booby traps or 'bushes. As long as we steer clear of moonshine stills.<br><br>
Hey, lots of Californ-eye-ans are moving to Tennessee. Wonder why? You definitely need a change of attitude. <br><br>
Come next summer and I will show you my pictures of the 'Nam - my second tour - 1998.<br><br>
Art,<br><br>
Me take a leak behind the barn? Sandals? Will bring back some Ho Chi Minh type A1 sandals.<br><br>
On a serious note. Getting back to your youthful pre Vietnam days in Maine - plant a garden. I have had one for the last 25 years. Always different. Always rewarding. Good for your mind and your soul.<br><br>
Bob-O,<br><br>
My first born is named Zachary. He just graduated from the U of Tennessee and is leaving in a few weeks to look for a job in Chicago. He is completing the circle which I began by leaving Chicago 25 years ago.<br><br>
Last, but not least, Ed. You are one hellava guy. You let the cat out of the bag last summer when you mentioned that you were &quot;putting up hay&quot; - that makes you a &quot;hay pitcher&quot;. <br><br>
Good to know you. *All of you*.<br><br>

<p><code>-- punkin rollers R us  (Anninimis) </code><p>


